@NODE Toolbox
@TITLE "The Toolbox Tools"
@PREV Main
@NEXT DM_TEXT

@{u}@{b}The Toolbox & Summary of Operations@{ub}@{uu}

@{u}Function Key:	F1@{uu}

	The tools of the @{b}ProVector«@{ub} toolbox are organized into three groups,
generally according to their purpose and the mode in which they are
effective. The top group, comprising the six tools in the first three rows,
is for creating new objects.  The middle four tools are global in their
effect, and may be used in conjunction with any of the other tools in the
toolbox.  The bottom group consists of the tools used to manipulate existing
objects.


@{u}The Toolbox Tools@{uu}

	@{"   Freehand   " link DM_FREEHAND}@{"    Drawing   " link DM_BEZIER}
	@{"   Rectangle  " link DM_RECTANGLE}@{"    Ellipse   " link DM_ELLIPSE}
	@{"     Text     " link DM_TEXT}@{"   Selection  " link OM_SELECT}
	-----------------------------
	@{" Grid Display " link GM_DISP}@{"   Grid Snap  " link GM_SNAP}
	@{"    Magnet    " link GM_MAGNET}@{"    Magnify   " link VM_INZOOM}
	-----------------------------
	@{"    Clone     " link OM_CLONE}@{"     Move     " link OM_MOVE}
	@{"    Rotate    " link OM_ROTATE}@{"     Scale    " link OM_SCALE}
	@{"    Front     " link OM_FRONT}@{"    Change    " link OM_CHANGE}
	@{"     Back     " link OM_BACK}@{"      Rx      " link OM_REXX}

	There are two exceptions to this generalization.  One is the @{b}Rx@{ub}
tool, which can be assigned by the user to execute an @{" ARexx " link OM_REXX} macro which
could both create and manipulate objects.  The other is the @{b}Selection @{ub}tool,
which is the last tool in the object creation group, but is perhaps more
closely associated with the object manipulation.

	Several of the tools have Shift-Select options that bring up
requesters for configuring the actions of the tools.

	The @{b}Drawing @{ub}tool is active by default.  Double-clicking the
Left-Mouse Button or pressing the Return (or Enter) key will complete an
object created with the @{b}Drawing@{ub} tool.  If the last point placed with the
@{b}Drawing@{ub} tool is near the first point of a new object, the object will be
closed; otherwise, it will be open (and unfilled).

	Newly created objects inherit the @{b}Current Attributes@{ub} (ie. fill
color, line color, etc.).  The Current Attributes are set by the Object
menu's Attributes... and Typeface... menu items.  If no object is selected
these menu items change the Current Attributes; if an object is selected,
these menu items affect the selected object (or objects).  The
@{" Status Window " link Status} displays the Current Attributes.

	Pressing the @{b}Backspace @{ub}key while entering points with the @{b}Drawing@{ub}
tool will undo (or delete) the most recently placed point.  You may use the
@{b}Backspace @{ub}key to successively undo all currently entered points to the
beginning of the object (Pressing the @{b}Esc@{ub} (Escape) key will cancel the
object altogether.

	You may move an object or a point of an object with a click-and-drag
operation.  If you press the @{b}Shift@{ub} key while moving an object, the move will
be constrained to either an exactly horizontal or exactly vertical move.

	Multiple objects may be selected by shift-clicking or lasso
selection (drag selection), then shift-click-and-dragging the objects or
points.  If you press and hold the @{b}Shift@{ub} key while moving the move will be
constrained to an exactly horizontal or vertical move.  If you release the
@{b}Shift@{ub} key while moving, the move will no longer be constrained.

	More complicated editing of the points of objects is possible by
double-clicking the Right-Mouse button on a selected point to bring up the
@{" Edit Object " link EdObj} pop-up menu.  This allows you to add or delete
points, add curves or straighten them, etc.

 	Pressing the @{b}Esc@{ub} (Escape) key will cancel any toolbox operation in
progress. For speed and convenience, ProVector allows you to interrupt
screen rendering (refreshing) when your next action is not dependent upon
viewing the results of your last action. To cause a refresh interrupt,
simply proceed with your next operation; any action, such as selecting a new
tool, clicking new points, choosing a menu item, etc. will cancel the
refresh in progress, and you can carry on with your desired operation.

	Occasionally, canceling a tool or interrupting a refresh may leave
the project window partially or even incorrectly rendered.  You can correct
this by pressing the @{b}Spacebar@{ub}.  The @{b}Spacebar@{ub} can force a refresh of the
project window any time you suspect your drawing is incorrectly rendered.

	Use the "F1" Function Key to open and close the Toolbox.

@ENDNODE


@NODE DM_FREEHAND
@TITLE "The Freehand Tool"
@TOC Toolbox
@PREV Toolbox
@NEXT DM_BEZIER

@{u}@{b}Tool:	Freehand@{ub}@{uu}

@{u}Hotkey: F@{uu}

	Select the @{b}Freehand@{ub} tool to create a freehand drawing.

/****** THE HELP FILES HAVE BEEN ABRIDGED FOR THIS DEMO RELEASE. ******/

	If you release the Left-Mouse_Button near the starting point of your
freehand object, the object will be closed; otherwise, it will be open (and
unfilled).

	Shift-clicking on the @{b}Freehand@{ub} tool opens the @{" Attributes " link OM_ATTRS} requester.
Also, see the @{b}Curve Tolerance@{ub} setting in the @{" Settings/Edit Prefs... " link SM_EDIT}
requester.

@ENDNODE


@NODE DM_BEZIER
@TITLE "The Drawing Tool"
@TOC Toolbox
@PREV DM_FREEHAND
@NEXT DM_RECTANGLE

@{u}@{b}Tool:	Drawing@{ub}@{uu}

@{u}Hotkey:	D@{uu}

	Select the @{b}Drawing@{ub} tool to create objects composed of both straight
lines and curves (B-splines).  If you want straight lines just click points
to place the ends of the line segments.

	To create a curve in ProVector, you must enter four points.  The
first and last points are called @{b}anchor@{ub} points; the second and third points
are @{b}control@{ub} points.  The anchor points define the beginning and end of the
curve along the outline of the object.  The distance and direction of the
control points modify the straight line formed by the anchor points. The
direction of the curve and the distance it is distorted from the straight
line is proportional to the distance and direction of the control points.

	To create a curve, click and release to place the first anchor, then
click and drag from the point of the second anchor.  At this stage you will
see an interactive rendering of the curve as you move the mouse.  Releasing
the Left-Mouse Button places the first control point.  Click to place the
second control point.  The rubber-banding will then jump to the last anchor
point, from which you can add more straight lines or another curve (clicking
and dragging the next point places the @{b}second@{ub} anchor of a subsequent curve).

	Double-clicking the @{b}second control@{ub} point (or the second point of a
line segment), or pressing the@{b} Return@{ub} key will complete the object.  If the
last point placed with the @{b}Drawing@{ub} tool is near the first point of the new
object, the object will be closed and filled with the current attributes;
otherwise, it will be open (and unfilled).

	If ProVector is in @{b}FastEdit@{ub} mode (see the @{" Settings/Edit Prefs... " link SM_EDIT}
menu item), the outline of the curve segment being created is not rendered
until all four points of the curve are entered.

	If you press the Shift key while clicking to add a point to your
object, the point will be constrained to form either a horizontal, vertical,
or 45 degree angle with the previous point.

	You can create sub-polygons (transparent holes) within an object
with the @{b}Ctrl@{ub} key (Control key).  Once you have defined the outer borders of
the object you are creating, you may create a sub-polygon within it by
pressing the @{b}Ctrl@{ub} key while clicking the Left-Mouse Button to place the next
point. Entering subsequent points (without pressing Ctrl) will define
the sub-polygon or hole.

	You may create sub-polygons within sub-polygons (nested sub-
polygons) in the same manner.  Sub-polygons may also be created with the
@{" Edit/Path/Merge " link OM_MERGE} menu item.

	Finally, shift-clicking on the @{b}Drawing@{ub} tool opens the @{" Attributes " link OM_ATTRS}
requester.

@ENDNODE


@NODE DM_RECTANGLE
@TITLE "The Rectangle Tool"
@TOC Toolbox
@PREV DM_BEZIER
@NEXT DM_REGULAR

@{b}@{u}Tool:	Rectangle@{uu}@{ub}

@{u}Hotkey:	R@{uu}

	Select the @{b}Rectangle@{ub} tool to create polygons of a given number of
sides.  The default is four sides (a rectangle).

/****** THE HELP FILES HAVE BEEN ABRIDGED FOR THIS DEMO RELEASE. ******/

	If you press the @{b}Shift@{ub} key while dragging out the rectangle, it will
be constrained to a square.

	Shift-clicking on the @{b}Rectangle@{ub} tool itself will open the
@{" Regular Polygon Control " link DM_REGULAR} requester.

@ENDNODE


@NODE DM_REGULAR
@TITLE "The Regular Polygon Control Requester"
@TOC Toolbox
@PREV DM_RECTANGLE
@NEXT DM_ELLIPSE


/****** THE HELP FILES HAVE BEEN ABRIDGED FOR THIS DEMO RELEASE. ******/

@ENDNODE


@NODE DM_ELLIPSE
@TITLE "The Ellipse Tool"
@TOC Toolbox
@PREV DM_REGULAR
@NEXT DM_ARC

@{b}@{u}Tool:	Ellipse@{uu}@{ub}

@{u}Hotkey: E@{uu}

	Select the @{b}Ellipse@{ub} tool to create ellipses, arcs, and pie-shaped
wedges.

/****** THE HELP FILES HAVE BEEN ABRIDGED FOR THIS DEMO RELEASE. ******/

	If you press the @{b}Shift@{ub} key while dragging out the ellipse, it will
be constrained to a circle.

	Shift-click on the @{b}Ellipse@{ub} tool to open the @{" Arc Control " link DM_ARC} requester.

@ENDNODE


@NODE DM_ARC
@TITLE "The Arc Control Requester"
@TOC Toolbox
@PREV DM_ELLIPSE
@NEXT DM_TEXT


/****** THE HELP FILES HAVE BEEN ABRIDGED FOR THIS DEMO RELEASE. ******/

@ENDNODE


@NODE DM_TEXT
@TITLE "The Text Tool"
@TOC Toolbox
@PREV DM_ARC
@NEXT TextField

@{u}@{b}Tool:	Text@{ub}@{uu}

@{u}Hotkey:	T@{uu}

	Select the @{b}Text@{ub} tool to create text objects.  Having selected this
tool, click to mark the baseline/starting point of your text.  The Edit Text
Contents window will open.  This is a simple text editor with a menu bar,
and hotkeys of its own, plus clipboard support.  For full documentation, see
the @{" TextField Text Editor " link TextField}.

	Enter the desired text into the window.  Your text may include new
lines (using the @{b}Return@{ub} key).  Additional text formatting capabilities are
available through the imbedded commands below.   Choose the @{b}Project/OK@{ub} menu
item when you are finished entering text.  The text will be displayed with
the currently selected typeface, point size, fill, and border attributes.

	Shift-clicking on the Text tool opens the @{" Type Control " link TM_TYPEFACE} requester.


@{u}Text On Path@{uu}

	If, when marking your text base line, you click on a previously
selected, ungrouped, open object, the text you type will follow the path of
the of the object.  This can be useful for a variety of special effects.


@{u}Imbedded Formatting Commands@{uu}

	ProVector 3 now supports imbedded text formatting commands in its
Text Objects.  The following commands are implemented:

	Backslash		\\
	Character Number	\cn(decimal number)	PDFDocEncoding
	Newline			\nl			Same as ASCII NewLine
	Horizontal Motion	\hm(points)
	Vertical Motion		\vm(points)
	Horizontal Spacing	\hs(points)
	Word Spacing		\ws(points)

	Fill Style		\fs(index)
	Fill Value		\fv(index)
	Edge Style		\es(index)
	Edge Value		\ev(index)
	Edge Weight		\ew(points)

	FontName		\fn("Fontname")		From Font List
	Point size		\ps(points)
	Aspect Ratio		\ar(ratio)
	Rotate			\ro(angle)
	Slant			\sl(angle)

	All imbedded commands are prefixed by the "\" (backslash) character.
To enter a backslash into your text object, you must enter double back-
slashes in the text editor.

	Most of the commands are self-evident, but a few could use clarifi-
cation.  The @{b}Character Number@{ub} command inserts a character referenced by its
decimal value in the font encoding table.  The @{b}Character Number@{ub} command
recognizes characters 24-255.  For the technically inclined, ProVector
supports Adobe PDFDocEncoding, which is an extension of ISOLatin1 character
set.  For the rest of us, sample project files, "OFNT_Codes.dr2d,"
"Type1_Codes.dr2d" and an ARexx macro, @{" ShowCharSet.pvrx " link PVRX.guide/ShowCharSet} can be found in
the "DR2D_Drawings" and "REXX" directories, repsectively.

	"OFNT_Codes.dr2d" and "Type1_Codes.dr2d" are identical files except
that "Type1_Codes.dr2d" requires "AvantGarde-Demi" to be in your Font
Manager's font list.  "OFNT_Codes.dr2d" uses "PV_Sans" included in the
ProVector distribution.  To see what decimal number is needed to insert any
character in a text object, load one of these files.  Characters 24-255 will
be displayed in the Default layer.  A locked layer will display the decimal
values of each, just beneath the respective characters.  You can perform an
@{" Edit/SelectAll " link EM_SELECT_ALL}, then select a new typeface with @{" Object/Typeface... " link TM_TYPEFACE} to see
the respective @{b}Character Number@{ub} required for any character in any typeface
you have in your ProVector font list.

/****** THE HELP FILES HAVE BEEN ABRIDGED FOR THIS DEMO RELEASE. ******/

	@{b}Note:@{ub} Text-on-path currently only supports @{b}Horizontal Motion@{ub}.

	See the files "OFNT_Sample.dr2d" and "Type1_Sample.dr2d" in the
"DR2D_Drawings" directory for examples of the use of the imbedded commands.
(These files are identical, except that the second file uses Palatino-Roman
and Palatino-Italic Adobe Type1 fonts, while the first uses OFNT fonts
supplied with ProVector.)


@{u}Editing Text@{uu}

	To edit the text of an existing text object, select the object with
the @{b}Selection@{ub} tool, then double-click over it with the Right-Mouse Button.
The text editor will open and display the contents of the text object.

	If you have a three-button mouse, or other input device that can
emulate a Middle-Mouse Button (such as a graphics tablet pen), a single-
click of the Middle-Mouse Button may be used instead of double-clicking with
the Right-Mouse Button.

@ENDNODE


@NODE TextField
@TITLE "The TextField Text Editor"
@TOC Toolbox
@PREV DM_TEXT
@NEXT OM_SELECT

@{b}@{u}The TextField Text Editor@{uu}@{ub}

	The TextField Text Editor utilizes the "textfield.gadget," an
object-oriented text editor by Mark Thomas.  The textfield.gadget, as
implemented in ProVector, has many of the standard features you would expect
in an Amiga text editor.  It has @{b}Project@{ub} and @{b}Edit@{ub} menus, click-and-drag text
high-lighting, and numerous keyboard shortcuts for editing and cursor
movement.


@{u}The TextField Menus@{uu}

@{b}Project/OK@{ub}

Command Key:	Right_Amiga-O

	When you are finished editing your text, choose the @{b}Project/OK@{ub} menu
item to have the text rendered into the project display.


@{b}Project/Cancel@{ub}

Command Key:	Right_Amiga-K

	If you wish to cancel the text editor without creating a new text
object, or reject changes you have just made to an existing text object,
choose the @{b}Project/Cancel@{ub} menu item.

	The window @{b}Close@{ub} gadget will also cancel the text editor


@{b}Project/About...@{ub}

Command Key:	Not available

	Choosing @{b}Project/About...@{ub} introduces you to a talented Amiga
programmer to whom Stylus, Inc. is grateful.


@{b}Edit/Cut@{ub}

Command Key:	Right_Amiga-X

	Cut marked text to clipboard.


@{b}Edit/Copy@{ub}

Command Key:	Right_Amiga-C

	Copy marked text to clipboard.


@{b}Edit/Paste@{ub}
Command Key:	Right_Amiga-V

	Paste current contents of the clipboard at cursor position, or
replace marked text with the clipboard contents (marked text is saved in
the undo buffer).


@{b}Edit/Erase@{ub}

Command Key:	Right_Amiga-E

	Erase all text (text is saved in undo buffer).


@{b}Edit/Undo@{ub}

Command Key:	Right_Amiga-U

	Undeletes (pastes) the last block of text marked, or recover from
Erase.


@{u}Marking Text@{uu}

	You can high-light text for cutting, copying, and erasing with a
simple click-and-drag of the mouse.  Pressing alphanumeric keys replaces
text that is highlighted.  The cursor keys move you to the start or end
of the highlighted text.

	While you drag to scroll, the farther away from the gadget your
mouse pointer is, the faster the gadget will scroll.


@{u}Hotkey Sequences@{uu}

	For hotkey sequences, the Amiga Style Guide was followed as closely
as possible.  The following hotkeys are supported:

    @{u}Hotkeys		Functions@{uu}


    @{b}Shift-Cursor_Up@{ub}	Move to the top line in the current page, or
			scroll up one page if cursor is on top line.

    @{b}Shift-Cursor_Down@{ub}	Move to the bottom line in the current page,
			or scroll down one page if cursor is on top
			line.

    @{b}Ctrl-Cursor_Right@{ub}	Move to the start of the current line.
    @{b}Shift-Cursor_Right@{ub}

    @{b}Ctrl-Cursor_Left@{ub}	Move to the end of the current line.
    @{b}Shift-Cursor_Left@{ub}

    @{b}Shift-Backspace@{ub}	Delete all text to the left of cursor on the current
			line.

    @{b}Shift-Delete@{ub}	Delete all text to the right of the cursor on the
			current line.

    @{b}Ctrl-Cursor_Up@{ub}	Move to the top line of text.

    @{b}Ctrl-Cursor_Down@{ub}	Move to the bottom line of text.

    @{b}Alt-Cursor_Right@{ub}	Move to the next word.

    @{b}Alt-Cursor_Left@{ub}	Move to the previous word.

    @{b}Alt-Cursor_Up@{ub}	Move to first character in the editor.

    @{b}Alt-Cursor_Down@{ub}	Move to last character in the editor.

    @{b}Alt-Backspace@{ub}	Deletes the word to the left of the cursor starting
			at the current cursor position.

    @{b}Alt-Del@{ub}		Deletes the word to the right of the cursor starting
			at the current cursor position.

    @{b}Ctrl-X@{ub}		Deletes the whole line that the cursor is on (line
			is saved in the undo buffer.

    @{b}Right_Amiga-A@{ub}	Mark all text.

When text is highlighted the following keys have functions:

    @{b}Backspace@{ub}		Erase marked text (text is saved in the undo
			buffer).

    @{b}Del@{ub}		Erase marked text (text is saved in the undo
			buffer).

    @{b}(any text key)@{ub}	Replace marked text with that character.


@{u}Developer Information on the TextField.Gadget@{uu}

	The textfield.gadget, by Mark Thomas, is an object-oriented text
editor of the Amiga BOOPSI gadget class.  As such, any Amiga program is
welcome to call on it.

	The archive, "textfield.lha" is available for anonymous FTP from the
AmiNet archives, and elswhere.  The archive contains licensing information
(very reasonable), as well as programmer documentation, and sample code
listings in both C and Oberon.

@ENDNODE


@NODE GM_DISP
@TITLE "The Grid Display Tool"
@TOC Toolbox
@PREV TextField
@NEXT GM_SNAP

@{u}@{b}Tool:	Grid Display@{ub}@{uu}

@{u}Hotkey: G@{uu}

	Selecting the @{b}Grid Display@{ub} tool displays a grid in the current
project window.

/****** THE HELP FILES HAVE BEEN ABRIDGED FOR THIS DEMO RELEASE. ******/

	Shift-clicking on the @{b}Grid Display@{ub} tool opens the @{" Grid Size " link VM_GRID}
requester for setting the spacing of the grid points.

@ENDNODE


@NODE GM_SNAP
@TITLE "The Grid Snap Tool"
@TOC Toolbox
@PREV GM_DISP
@NEXT GM_MAGNET

@{b}@{u}Tool:	Grid Snap@{uu}@{ub}

@{u}Hotkey: g@{uu}

	Selecting the @{b}Grid Snap@{ub} tool causes your input points to be snapped
to the grid intersections.

/****** THE HELP FILES HAVE BEEN ABRIDGED FOR THIS DEMO RELEASE. ******/

	Shift-clicking on the @{b}Grid Snap@{ub} tool opens the @{" Grid Size " link VM_GRID} requester
for setting the spacing of the grid points.

@ENDNODE


@NODE GM_MAGNET
@TITLE "The Magnet Tool"
@TOC ToolBox
@PREV GM_SNAP
@NEXT VM_INZOOM

@{b}@{u}Tool:	Magnet@{uu}@{ub}

@{u}Hotkey: M@{uu}

	Select the @{b}Magnet@{ub} tool to assign "magnetism" to the currently
selected objects. When the left-mouse button is clicked within a specified
distance of an object which has been "magnetized," it will be drawn to that
object.  The effect is similar to the mouse snapping to the grid when the
@{" Grid Snap " link GM_SNAP} tool is selected.  If you are creating a new object, the new
points clicked within the range of the "magnetized" object will snap to its
border. In this way the new object can be given a perfectly contiguous edge
with the "magnetized" object.

	To "magnetize" an object or objects, @{" Select " link OM_SELECT} (high-light) them,
then click on the @{b}Magnet@{ub} tool.   Note that previously "magnetized" objects
will be "demagnetized" by this action.  The @{b}Magnet@{ub} tool will remain
high-lighted as long as there are "magnetized" objects. If you click on the
Magnet tool when no objects are selected, all "magnetized" objects will be
"demagnetized."

	Like the @{b}Grid@{ub} tools and the @{b}Magnify@{ub} tool, the @{b}Magnet@{ub} tool can be
selected at any stage of object creation or manipulation.  Virtually all
toolbox operations which expect additional input are affected by
"magnetism," including the @{b}Magnify@{ub} tool.

@ENDNODE


@NODE VM_INZOOM
@TITLE "The Magnify Tool"
@TOC Toolbox
@PREV GM_MAGNET
@NEXT VM_OUTZOOM

@{b}@{u}Tool:	Magnify@{uu}@{ub}

@{u}Hotkey: z@{uu}

	Select the @{b}Magnify@{ub} tool to "Zoom in" on an area of your project to
do detailed work.

/****** THE HELP FILES HAVE BEEN ABRIDGED FOR THIS DEMO RELEASE. ******/

	The @{b}Magnify@{ub} tool can be activated at almost any stage of creating or
editing an object.  Simply click on the tool, click-and-drag to set the
desired magnification, and resume entering points, manipulating the object,
etc.

@ENDNODE


@NODE VM_OUTZOOM
@TITLE "Zooming Out"
@TOC Toolbox
@PREV VM_INZOOM
@NEXT OM_SELECT

@{b}@{u}Tool:	Zoom Out@{uu}@{ub}

@{u}Hotkey: Z@{uu}

	Shift-click on the @{b}Magnify@{ub} tool to "zoom out" from the portion of
your project that is currently displayed.

/****** THE HELP FILES HAVE BEEN ABRIDGED FOR THIS DEMO RELEASE. ******/

@ENDNODE


@NODE OM_SELECT
@TITLE "The Selection Tool"
@TOC Toolbox
@PREV VM_INZOOM
@NEXT OM_SHFTSEL

@{b}@{u}Tool:	Selection@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}Hotkey:	S@{ub}

	This tool is the @{b}Selection@{ub} tool.  It is used to select existing
objects for manipulation by other ProVector tools and menu items.

	Object selection varies slightly depending upon whether you are in
@{b}Wireframe@{ub} or @{b}Preview@{ub} mode (see the Preview checkbox in the @{" Edit Prefs " link SM_EDIT}
requester), and whether an object is filled or unfilled.  If you are in
@{b}Preview@{ub} mode, you may click the Left-Mouse Button anywhere within the
boundaries of a filled object to select it; while if you are in Wireframe
mode, you must click directly upon the outline of the object to select it.
In @{b}Wireframe@{ub} mode, you may actually click through a filled object, to select
the outline of an object underneath.  You must always click on the outline
of an unfilled object to select it.

	The points of the object will highlight to indicate that it is
selected.  If you click on a second object, the previous one will deselect.
To select multiple objects, shift-select them (i.e. click on additional
objects with the Left-Mouse Button while holding down either @{b}Shift@{ub} key).

	Once you have selected the desired objects, you may manipulate them
with the @{b}Edit@{ub} menu items, the object manipulation tools and the
@{" Edit Object " link EdObj} pop-up menu.

	If you click @{b}inside@{ub} the boundaries of any object, and move the mouse
without releasing the Left-Mouse Button (click-and-drag), the object will
attach itself to the Mouse Pointer (the @{b}Move@{ub} tool will also highlight).
When you release the Left-Mouse Button, the object will be placed at the new
position of the Mouse Poiner.  If you click-and-drag while holding down
either @{b}Shift@{ub} key, and multiple objects are selected, all of the selected
objects will move in relation to the Mouse Pointer.  This @{b}Implicit Move@{ub}
function eliminates the need to select the @{b}Move@{ub} tool before moving objects.
There are, however, occasions when it is useful to explicitly activate the
@{b}Move@{ub} tool prior to a move.  See the @{" Move " link OM_MOVE} tool.

	If you click-and-drag the Mouse Pointer on a point of a previously
selected object, the point will attach itself to the Mouse Pointer.  When
you release the Left-Mouse Button, the point will be placed at the new
position of the Mouse Poiner.

	If you click-and-drag the Mouse Pointer @{b}outside@{ub} the boundaries of
any object, and move the mouse without releasing the Left-Mouse Button
(click-and-drag), a rubber band stretching out from the initial point will
attach itself to the Mouse Pointer.  When you release the Left-Mouse Button,
all objects @{b}completely enclosed@{ub} by this bounding box will be selected.  This
is called @{b}Lasso Selection@{ub}.

	If you wish to lasso select several objects on top of a larger,
background object that you do not wish selected, you may force lasso
selection by shift-clicking on the @{b}Selection@{ub} tool.  Now when you click on
the background object, instead of selecting that object, the lasso will
appear and you may select just the objects that you want.

	To de-select only one of several selected objects, press the @{b}Alt@{ub} key
while clicking on it.  Pressing the @{b}Alt@{ub} key while clicking on an object will
alternate the selection state of the object.  Thus, if the object is
selected, it will be deselected; if the object is not selected it will be
selected.  This will not effect any other object.

	Choose the @{" Edit/Select All " link EM_SELECT_ALL} menu item.  To de-select all selected
objects, simply click on the previously activated Selection tool.

	If the object you wish to manipulate is already selected (such as a
newly created object), it is not necessary to select this tool before
choosing a manipulation tool.

@ENDNODE


@NODE OM_SHFTSEL
@TITLE "Lasso Selection"
@TOC Toolbox
@PREV OM_SHFTSEL
@NEXT OM_CLONE

@{b}@{u}Tool:	 Shift Selection@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}Hotkey:	 Not available@{ub}

	Shift-clicking on the @{b}Selection@{ub} tool activates lasso selection. To
lasso select objects, first click on a corner of the area you wish to lasso
select, and move the mouse without releasing the Left-Mouse Button
(click-and-drag).  A rectangular "rubberband" will attach itself to your
Mouse Pointer. "Stretch" the rubberband by dragging the mouse, until it
encloses all the objects you wish to select, then release the mouse button.
@{b}all points@{ub} of an object must be @{b}completely enclosed@{ub} by the box to become
selected.

	Click-and-draging the Mouse Pointer outside the boundaries of any
object, while the @{b}Selection@{ub} tool is active will also initiate lasso
selection.

	Note that shift-clicking on the @{b}Selection@{ub} tool @{b}forces@{ub} lasso
selection.  If you wish to lasso select several objects on top of a larger,
background object that you do not wish selected, you should force lasso
selection.  Then, when you click-and-drag on the background object, instead
of selecting and moving that object, the lasso will appear and you may
select just the objects that you want.

@ENDNODE


@NODE OM_CLONE
@TITLE "The Clone Tool"
@TOC Toolbox
@PREV OM_SHFTSEL
@NEXT EM_DELETE

@{b}@{u}Tool:	Clone@{uu}@{ub}

@{u}Hotkey:	c@{uu}

	Select the @{b}Clone@{ub} tool to duplicate the currently selected object(s).

/****** THE HELP FILES HAVE BEEN ABRIDGED FOR THIS DEMO RELEASE. ******/

@ENDNODE


@NODE OM_MOVE
@TITLE "The Move Tool"
@TOC Toolbox
@PREV EM_DELETE
@NEXT OM_MOVE_CONTROL

@{b}@{u}Tool:	Move@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}Hotkey:	m@{ub}

	Select the @{b}Move@{ub} tool to explicitly move the currently selected
object(s) to a different position.  (NOTE: It is not required to activate
this tool before moving objects.  Selecting an object with the @{b}Selection@{ub}
tool, using click-and-drag, will implictly move an object.  See the
@{" Selection " link OM_SELECT} tool for more information.)

	After clicking on this tool, click and hold the Left-Mouse Button on
an object.  As you drag the Mouse Pointer, the object's outline will follow
it.  Position the outline where you wish to move the object, and release the
mouse button.  When the move is completed, the object will remain selected.

	If more than one object is selected, the other objects will also
move in relation to the Mouse Pointer.

	If you press and hold the @{b}Shift@{ub} key while moving an object, the move
will be constrained to either an exactly horizontal or exactly vertical move.
If you release the @{b}Shift@{ub} key while moving, the move will no longer be
constrained.

	In @{b}FastEdit@{ub} mode, a bounding-box is used to represent the object(s)
as it is moved.  See the @{" Settings/Edit Prefs... " link SM_EDIT} menu item.

	Shift-clicking on the @{b}Move@{ub} tool opens the @{" Move Control " link OM_MOVE_CONTROL} requester.

	It is sometimes useful to explicitly activate the @{b}Move@{ub} tool prior to
a move, rather than using the @{b}Implicit Move@{ub} of the @{b}Selection@{ub} tool.  For
instance, if the object you wish to move is very small, its points may be so
close together that when you attempt to move the object, one of its points
moves instead.  By explicitly selecting the @{b}Move@{ub} tool, this confusion can be
avoided.

	Another example of the use of an explicit move, would be if you
wished to pick up the object and move it exactly by one of its points.  By
Magnetizing (see the @{" Magnet " link GM_MAGNET} tool) the object you can exactly click on the
point, but with an implicit move, only the point would move.  By explicitly
selecting the @{b}Move@{ub} tool, the whole object moves.

@ENDNODE


@NODE OM_MOVE_CONTROL
@TITLE "The Move Control Requester"
@TOC Toolbox
@PREV OM_MOVE
@NEXT OM_ROTATE


/****** THE HELP FILES HAVE BEEN ABRIDGED FOR THIS DEMO RELEASE. ******/

@ENDNODE


@NODE OM_ROTATE
@TITLE "The Rotate Tool"
@TOC Toolbox
@PREV OM_MOVE_CONTROL
@NEXT OM_ROT_CONTROL

@{b}@{u}Tool:	Rotate@{uu}@{ub}

@{u}Hotkey:	r@{uu}

	Select the @{b}Rotate@{ub} tool to rotate the currently selected object(s).

/****** THE HELP FILES HAVE BEEN ABRIDGED FOR THIS DEMO RELEASE. ******/

	Shift-clicking on the @{b}Rotate@{ub} tool opens the @{" Rotate Control " link OM_ROT_CONTROL}
requester.

@ENDNODE


@NODE OM_ROT_CONTROL
@TITLE "The Rotate Control Requester"
@TOC Toolbox
@PREV OM_ROTATE
@NEXT OM_SCALE


